I"x*<p>In this post, we will see an overview about all the knowledge learned in the Lisbon summer camp - Mobile section. There we go:</p>

<h3 id="building-auraplayer-web-services">Building AuraPlayer web Services</h3>

<p>First, we created REST web services to manage the Forms summit application using AuraPlayer’s Service Manager. We used IE to launch the summit Forms.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/AuraPlayerServiceManager.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>We created several services, pushing the button “record services.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/AuraPlayer-createService.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Then we defined the service name an the form URL. The URL form is connected to a Forms Server where AuraPlayer is installed. We have some options that we can use on AuraPlayer Manager in the record time.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/AuraPlayer-optionsRecordTime.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Also, we handled a “Oracle Forms” window that was opened automatically on IE.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/AuraPlayer-OracleForms.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Every time that we wanted to save and stop the recording, we pushed Save &amp; Exit.
<img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/AuraPlayer-saveAndExit.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>To test the services, from the “Service Details” page, we used the “Test” button
<img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/AuraPlayer-testButton.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Then the Service Tester page is displayed, The input parameters frame displays the values that would be sent to the service in this test.</p>

<p>The result could be displayed as XML or JSON if the “Show as Json chekbox” was checked.</p>

<h3 id="building-mcs-custom-api">Building MCS CUSTOM API</h3>

<p>We accesed to Mobile cloud service page and we a went to Applications -&gt; MobileBack Ends. Then we created a new backend.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-Backend.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Then we created a new Mobile BackEnd.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-createBackEnd.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>The details of the new Backend are displayed and we continued to design it.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-createBackEnd-2.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>We added new resources like apis and connectors, I will show bellow:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Create custom APIs:</li>
</ul>

<p>Select APIs</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APIS.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Then New API, we entered the API name and a short description.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APIDetails.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>On the security option set the “Login Required” to “OFF”.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APIsecurity.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>On the Endpoints option we created new resources, there we could define the path, type of the Method and the description of the endpoint.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APIResources.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>For each resource we could define the Request, Responses and Media Types.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APISMethods.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>To check the validation of the json sample data we used an online tool like: http://www.jsoneditoronline.org/</p>

<p>At the end of the session we created several resources as the image bellow:</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APIlistResources.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>On the schema option we created schemas to relate with the json content handled by the REST services.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APISchemas.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<ul>
  <li>Create REST connector</li>
</ul>

<p>Select connectors</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-Connectors.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Then we defined the Api name and the Remote URL that we created using AuraPlayer manager.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-ConnectorsDetails.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>We could test the created services using the endpoint URLs.
 <img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-ConnectorsTest.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>Then we modified the implementation of the APIS to use the connectors created previously. In the API section we went to the Implementation option and downloaded the API implementation pressing the Javascript scaffold green button in the center.</p>

<p><img src="/images/2016-09-16-Lisbon-summer-camp-mobile-learning-2016/MCS-APIimplementation.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<p>The archive file is downloaded in the computer and it contained 4 files, package.json, ReadMe.md, samples.txt and summitapplicationapi_00.js.</p>

<ul>
  <li>package.json includes metadata about the API.</li>
  <li>ReadMe.md includes explanation about the other files.</li>
  <li>Samples.txt contains a selection of Oracle MCS custom code examples</li>
  <li>summitapplicationapi_00.js is the main javascript file. The functions included in the javascript file define where we are expecting API implementation code to appear.</li>
</ul>

<p>package.json</p>

<div class="language-javascript highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>  <span class="p">{</span>
